Class BatchCollector<T extends @Nullable Object, K>

java.lang.Object
com.dua3.utility.lang.BatchCollector<T,K>
Type Parameters:
T - the item type
K - the key type
All Implemented Interfaces:
Collector<T, Deque<Pair<K,List<T>>>, List<Pair<K,List<T>>>>
public class BatchCollector<T extends @Nullable Object, K> extends Object implements Collector<T, Deque<Pair<K,List<T>>>, List<Pair<K,List<T>>>>
A collector that puts subsequent items into batches. A new batch is started by generating a new batch key.

Example: This code collects strings based on their length and places them in buckets. 

    BatchCollector<String, Integer> bc = new BatchCollector<>(s -> s != null ? s.length() : null);
    var result = Stream.of("one", "two", "three", "four", "five", "six").collect(bc);
The result will be a List<Integer, Pair<Integer, List<String>> equal to this one: 
    List.of(
        Pair.of(3, List.of("one", "two"),
        Pair.of(5, List.of("three"),
        Pair.of(4, List.of("four", "five"),
        Pair.of(3, List.of("six")
    )

Note: For Java 24+, have a look at stream gatherers (JEP 461, JEP 485) that might be a better fit for your use case.

  • Constructor Details

    • BatchCollector

      public BatchCollector(Function<? super T, ? extends K> keyMapper)
      Create a new BatchCollector.

      For each item in the stream, a key is determined by applying the keyMapper. If the generated key equals the last item's key, the item is added to the current batch. If not, a new batch is created and the item added.

      Parameters:
      keyMapper - mapping that maps each item to the grouping key

    • BatchCollector

      public BatchCollector(Function<? super T, ? extends @Nullable K> keyMapper, K defaultKey)
      Create a new BatchCollector that uses a default key value for items where the key mapper returns null.

      Use this constructor if the keymapper might return null.

      Parameters:
      keyMapper - the key mapper
      defaultKey - the default key
